      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h3>Who needs on-premise MDM</h3>
          <p>For a growing number of organizations regulated industries, government agencies, high-security enterprises, and globally distributed teams sending device telemetry to a vendor's cloud creates a compliance, sovereignty, or architecture problem that cloud-only MDMs simply cannot solve.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="feature-row">
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>Global Enterprises</h5>
            <p>Multinational companies operating in jurisdictions with strict data localization laws need device management that keeps data within specific geographic boundaries.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>Financial Services</h5>
            <p>Banks and payment processors operate under regulations that restrict where employee device data can reside. DORA, SOX, and PCI-DSS often prohibit third-party cloud storage of endpoint telemetry.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>Healthcare &amp; Life Sciences</h5>
            <p>HIPAA-covered entities managing devices that access PHI need endpoint management with full data residency control. Sending device inventory to a vendor cloud creates BAA complexity and audit risk.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>Critical Infrastructure</h5>
            <p>Energy, utilities, and industrial control environments require device management in isolated network segments. Cloud connectivity is either prohibited or architecturally impossible.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>Government &amp; Defense</h5>
            <p>Federal agencies and defense contractors require device management within a classified or controlled network boundary. Device telemetry cannot traverse the public internet.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature-item">
            <h5>Research &amp; Universities</h5>
            <p>Research institutions with government grants or export control requirements (ITAR/EAR) cannot allow device management data to reside on commercial cloud infrastructure.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>


      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h3>The problem with cloud-only MDM</h3>
          <p>Most modern MDMs are cloud-first. Device inventory, policy results, and user data flow through vendor infrastructure. For strict data governance requirements, that's a structural blocker.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="section-quote">
          <p purpose="quote-text">"Every other MDM vendor told us our data had to live in their cloud. Fleet was the only one that said run it on your own infrastructure. Same features, no exceptions."</p>
          <div purpose="quote-author-info">
            <p purpose="author-name">IT Security Architecture</p>
            <p purpose="author-title">Financial services, Fortune 100</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>


      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="section-heading">
          <h3>How Fleet on-premise works</h3>
          <p>Fleet runs on infrastructure you control: AWS, GCP, Azure, bare metal, or air-gapped. Simple to deploy, fully auditable, and designed to operate without calling home.</p>
        </div>

        <div purpose="three-column-list">
          <div purpose="feature">
            <p purpose="feature-headline">On-premise data center</p>
            <p purpose="feature-text">Bare metal or VMware, Docker or Kubernetes. No internet egress required.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature">
            <p purpose="feature-headline">Classified / air-gapped networks</p>
            <p purpose="feature-text">Zero outbound internet dependency. Package all assets for offline deployment and distribute via internal artifact repositories.</p>
          </div>
          <div purpose="feature">
            <p purpose="feature-headline">AWS / GCP / Azure</p>
            <p purpose="feature-text">Terraform into your own cloud account. VPC-isolated, no cross-account data access, no vendor visibility.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div purpose="landing-page-section">
        <div purpose="feature-with-image" class="d-flex flex-lg-row flex-column justify-content-between mx-auto align-items-start">
          <div purpose="feature-text" class="d-flex flex-column">
            <h3>Deploy on your infrastructure. Own every byte of your data.</h3>
            <p>Spin up Fleet using the official Terraform module, Helm chart, or Docker Compose. Fleet's architecture is a single binary + database no microservices sprawl, no vendor agents phoning home, no surprise egress.</p>
            <div purpose="checklist" class="flex-column d-flex">
              <p>Device enrollment points to your own Fleet instance, not a vendor cloud</p>
              <p>Every MDM command and query result stays inside your network</p>
              <p>Auditors can verify zero outbound traffic to vendor infrastructure</p>
              <p>Upgrade on your schedule: no forced updates, no deprecation emails</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div purpose="terminal-block">
            <div purpose="terminal-bar">
              <span purpose="terminal-dot" class="dot-red"></span>
              <span purpose="terminal-dot" class="dot-yellow"></span>
              <span purpose="terminal-dot" class="dot-green"></span>
              <span purpose="terminal-filename">main.tf your AWS account</span>
            </div>
            <pre purpose="terminal-body"><span purpose="tc"># Deploy Fleet in your own AWS account</span>
<span purpose="tk">module</span> <span purpose="ts">"fleet"</span> {
  <span purpose="tk">source</span>  = <span purpose="ts">"github.com/fleetdm/fleet-terraform"</span>
  <span purpose="tk">version</span> = <span purpose="ts">"~> 8.0"</span>

  <span purpose="tk">vpc_id</span>     = <span purpose="ts">var.vpc_id</span>
  <span purpose="tk">subnet_ids</span> = <span purpose="ts">var.private_subnet_ids</span>
  <span purpose="tk">license_key</span> = <span purpose="ts">var.license_key</span>
}

<span purpose="tc"># Data residency: your VPC only.</span>
<span purpose="tc"># Audit logs: your CloudTrail. Your SIEM.</span></pre>
